&nbsp;
Before delivery, the Red Cross Delegate > was put on stage and signed the documents > that a militiaman of Hamas has brought them. On the same stage the three who, next to armed militiamen, spoke briefly to the microphone one after the other, > in a ceremony of a few minutes well studied and less chaotic than the previous occasions. &nbsp;Horn, Troufanov and Dekel-Chen were then climbed to the Red Cross.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The bus convoy with 333 Palestinian prisoners released from Israel arrived in Khan Younis, in southern Gaza, shortly after 12:30 Italian time. Images of the arrival of prisoners, welcomed as always by a crowd, were transmitted by the Jazeera.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Who are the freed hostages
All men, all with dual nationality and all abducted at the kibbutz of Nir Oz the three hostages released today by Hamas and Islamic Jihad, in the sixth exchange of prisoners provided by the truce agreement. From the entry into force of the ceasefire on 19 January, 19 Israeli hostages were released with dual nationality, plus five Thai hostages outside the agreement.
&nbsp;
In total, the first phase of the agreement, which will last six weeks, provides for the return of 33 hostages, of which eight declared dead, in exchange for about 1,900 Palestinians > held by Israel, of which 369 are free today.
<br> Here are the three men who have been able to reabbreach their families today.<br> - Sacha Troufanov, Russian-Israeli >, is 29 years in prison. He was kidnapped on October 7, 2023 with his companion Sapir Cohen, mother Elena Troufanov and grandmother Irena Tati, all released during the first truce of November 2023. His father, Vitali, was killed during the attack. The Troufanov family emigrated from Russia to Israel in the late 1990s.<br> - Yair Horn, Israeli-Argentine, > 46 years old, was kidnapped in his house in the kibbutz Nir Oz along with his brother Eitan Horn (38 years old), who had gone to visit him. He was among 33 people waiting for priority liberation because he was sick of diabetes.><br> Before his capture, Yair Horn, who worked in construction, was very involved in the life of kibbutz, organized parties and was responsible for the pub. The Horn family emigrated from Argentina years ago, according to the Israeli press.<br> - Sagui Dekel-Chen, 36 years old, Israeli-American >, had been taken while trying to protect the pregnant wife and the two daughters, and held prisoner by the Islamic Jihad. After his capture, his wife Avital gave birth to their third daughter, called Shahar, Alba, in Hebrew, in December 2023. Renowned all-rounder, Sagui is also an amateur musician. He is the son of a history professor at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
<h2> Wave: 61% Israeli is in favour of the second stage of the agreement
The majority of the Israelis are in favour of maintaining the truce agreement with Hamas to ensure the release of the remaining hostages rather than resume the war. It emerged from a survey by the public broadcaster Kan, of which the Times of Israel refers.><br> 61% of respondents responded that Israel should continue with the second stage, 18% responded that Israel should return to war > and 21% did not take a position.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Netanyahu: "Through Trump also"</h2>
&nbsp; Israeli premier Benjamin Netanyahu has exulted for the release of three more hostages this morning, merit, said, also of American President Donald Trump.
"Even this week Hamas attempted to violate the agreement and > create a false crisis with false accusations," said Netanyahu, according to the Israeli media.<br> The release of the hostages, > explained, is due to the support of US President Donald Trump and the "concentration of our forces in the Strip and the clear and unequivocal statements of President Trump".<br> Now "we are working in full co-ordination with the United States to free all our hostages, alive and dead as soon as possible, and we are preparing with the utmost intensity for what will come next, in all senses," warned Netanyahu.
&nbsp;
<h2>Moscow thanks Egypt and Qatar for liberation Troufanov</h2>
Moscow thanked the Palestinians, Egypt and Qatar for the release of the Russian-Israeli hostage Alexander Troufanov, one of three prisoners released today by Hamas.
"We are grateful to the Palestinian side and our partners qatarini and Egyptians > for their help in the favourable outcome of this case. We would like to emphasize that freeing our compatriots from captivity was and remains our priority", said the spokesman of the Russian Foreign Ministry Maria Zakharova in a note<br> Now the goal is "the ready return home > of our other fellow country remained in Gaza, [Maxim] Kharkin, born in Donbas>", added Zakharova.
