AGI - As expected, the first day of the Munich conference was dominated by the Ukrainian question. And as it was foreseeable, beyond the reassurances of all that the final goal remains a just peace, the approach of the United States and Europe towards Russia and the idea on which will be the final compromise diverge and not little. American vice president J.D. Vence arrived in Bavaria to clarify to those who had so far hoped for a rethink that "there is a new sheriff" in Washington. His name is Donald Trump and he'll do everything opposite to what his predecessor had done, Joe Biden. Starting with the war in Ukraine.
&nbsp;
From the stage of the conference, Vance reiterated the American 'bastone and carrot' approach. "We trust in a reasonable agreement between Ukraine and Russia," he said, "there are economic pressure levers and, of course, military pressure levers." The option of sending U.S. troops to Ukraine America "remains on the agenda" if Moscow refused the negotiation. But opening up to Washington's compromise is such that the hypothesis is considered remote. "We want the war to end, we want people to stop being killed, but we want to reach a lasting peace, not a peace that brings Eastern Europe back into conflict after a couple of years," he assured. Clearly the reference to the words of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky that even before his intervention at the Conference had launched the alarm on the risk that Russia attacks NATO countries next year.
&nbsp;
But Zelensky doesn't seem to trust American reassurances. Only if Donald Trump "chooses our side and not a middle position, he can push Putin to end the war," he warned. Certainly, no step is possible on the Ukrainian side before an agreement with America. The Ukrainian leader is willing to see President Vladimir Putin, and no one else on the Russian side, and "only after we have a common plan with Trump. I don't want to go to history for allowing Vladimir Putin to occupy my country." That said, "we are ready to move as quickly as possible towards real and guaranteed peace." And the strongest guarantee is called NATO. "I am pragmatic, NATO remains the cheapest option," the Ukrainian president warned, explaining that in the absence of a Kiev entry into the alliance, Europe should spend huge resources to defend it.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
But that there is little enthusiasm from different parts, so much so that the Secretary-General of the Alliance, Martk Rutte, has braked. "I know that many think that part of the peace agreement should be NATO membership, but it has never been promised to Ukraine that membership would be part of the agreement," he clarified.
&nbsp;
The President of the European Commission, Ursula Von der Leyen, also spoke of the possible repercussions on the United States of a weak agreement. "A failed Ukraine would weaken Europe, but it would also weaken the United States," he warned from Monaco "that's why it's so important that we do things well." Skeptic on Moscow's intentions remains the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policy, Kaja Kallas, after the Russian attack in the night at Chernobyl. "They are unacceptable attacks," he said, "and once again demonstrate that Russia does not seek peace."
&nbsp;
But the EU, at least for now, seems to watch the game even from the bench, but from the sides. In order to appease Europeans, outraged for exclusion from any table, Vance today assured that Europe will "certainly" a role. On this the twenty-seven found the shore of China: "Europe must be involved" in the peace negotiations, said Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi. If, how and when everything remains to be seen.&nbsp;

